The problem asks for the probability that the product of $n$ digits drawn uniformly from $\{1, \dots, 9\}$ is divisible by 10.
Let $D = \{1, \dots, 9\}$. The total number of sequences is $9^n$.
A sequence product is divisible by 10 if and only if it is divisible by 2 and by 5.
Let $A$ be the set of sequences where the product is not divisible by 2 (i.e., no digit is even). The even digits in $D$ are $\{2, 4, 6, 8\}$, so the odd digits are $\{1, 3, 5, 7, 9\}$. $|A| = 5^n$.
Let $B$ be the set of sequences where the product is not divisible by 5 (i.e., no digit is 5). The digits not divisible by 5 are $\{1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 7, 8, 9\}$. $|B| = 8^n$.
The set of sequences where the product is not divisible by 10 is $A \cup B$.
The size is $|A \cup B| = |A| + |B| - |A \cap B|$.
$A \cap B$ is the set of sequences with digits that are neither even nor 5. These are $\{1, 3, 7, 9\}$. $|A \cap B| = 4^n$.
So $|A \cup B| = 5^n + 8^n - 4^n$.
The number of "good" sequences is $9^n - (5^n + 8^n - 4^n)$.
The probability is $(9^n - 5^n - 8^n + 4^n) / 9^n = 1 - (5/9)^n - (8/9)^n + (4/9)^n$.
This matches the `solution` definition (modulo ENNReal subtraction ordering for small $n$).

